\par\line\par

{\f1\fs32\b\cf2 SECTION 2 \emdash PROBLEM STATEMENT & PROJECT CONTEXT\par}
{\f1\fs20\cf6\i [Duration: ~2 minutes]\par}
\par

{\f1\fs22 Sri Lanka\rquote s public bus network is one of the most heavily used transport systems in the country, yet it operates almost entirely without digital support. Commuters have no way to know where a bus is, how full it is, or when it will arrive. Drivers have no digital tools to report emergencies or log trips. Administrators manage fleets manually with no real-time visibility.\par
\par
\b BusGo solves all three problems simultaneously.\b0\par
\par
The system provides:\par
{\pard\li720
\f1\bullet  Real-time bus tracking on live maps for both passengers and administrators.\par
\bullet  A structured digital workflow for drivers to log trips, report emergencies, and receive route information.\par
\bullet  A QR-code-based ticketing system for quick and paperless boarding.\par
\bullet  A centralized admin control panel to oversee the full fleet, manage users, respond to emergencies, and maintain audit trails.\par
\par}
The entire system is built around three Colombo metropolitan bus routes: Route 138 (Nugegoda to Colombo Fort), Route 163 (Rajagiriya to Maharagama), and Route 171 (Colombo 4 to Athurugiriya) \emdash routes chosen because of their high ridership and geographic coverage of the Colombo district.\par
}
\par\line\par

{\f1\fs32\b\cf2 SECTION 3 \emdash SYSTEM ARCHITECTURE OVERVIEW\par}
{\f1\fs20\cf6\i [Duration: ~2 minutes | Point to architecture diagram if available]\par}
\par

{\f1\fs22 Before diving into my front-end work specifically, let me briefly describe how the overall system is structured so my work makes sense in context.\par
\par
\b BusGo follows a layered client-server architecture with four front-end applications connecting to a shared backend:\par\b0
\par
{\pard\li720
\b Backend:\b0  A Node.js and Express.js REST API server, using Supabase as the cloud database and Supabase Realtime for live event broadcasting.\par
\b Admin Panel:\b0  A React 19 + TypeScript web application \emdash my work.\par
\b Passenger Mobile App (BusGo Client):\b0  A Flutter application for passengers \emdash my work.\par
\b Driver Mobile App (BusGo Drive):\b0  A Flutter application for bus drivers \emdash my work.\par
\b Scanner App (BusGo Scanner):\b0  A Flutter application for ticket conductors \emdash my work.\par
\par}
All four front-end applications communicate with the backend through a secured REST API, and the mobile apps also subscribe to Supabase Realtime for live bus location broadcasts.\par
\par
My role was entirely on the \b client layer\b0 . I was responsible for designing and implementing all four of these front-end applications, ensuring they were production-ready, responsive, and connected correctly to the backend API.\par
}
\par\line\par

{\f1\fs32\b\cf2 SECTION 4 \emdash ADMIN WEB PANEL (REACT)\par}
{\f1\fs20\cf6\i [Duration: ~5\endash 6 minutes | Demo the panel if possible]\par}
\par

{\f1\fs28\b\cf2 4.1 Technology Stack \emdash Admin Panel\par}
\par
{\f1\fs22 For the Admin Panel, I chose the following stack:\par
\par
{\pard\li720
\b React 19\b0  with \b TypeScript\b0  \emdash React is the industry standard for building component-based web UIs. TypeScript was chosen to catch type errors at compile time rather than at runtime, which is critical for a production system where data shapes from the API can be complex.\par
\b Vite\b0  \emdash Used as the build tool for its extremely fast hot module replacement during development and optimised production bundles.\par
\b React Router v7\b0  \emdash For client-side routing with protected routes.\par
\b React Leaflet\b0  \emdash For rendering interactive maps. Leaflet was chosen over Google Maps because it is open-source, does not require API key billing, and integrates well with OpenStreetMap tiles.\par
\b Axios\b0  \emdash For API communication with the backend, wrapped in a central service layer.\par
\b Lucide React\b0  \emdash For a consistent, lightweight icon library throughout the UI.\par
\par}
}

{\f1\fs28\b\cf2 4.2 Application Structure\par}
\par
{\f1\fs22 The admin panel is structured around a \b protected route system\b0 . Any user who is not authenticated is automatically redirected to the login page. Once logged in as an administrator, the panel uses a persistent \b sidebar layout\b0  with a main content area, giving the feel of a native desktop application.\par
\par
The routes are:\par
{\pard\li720
\b /admin/login\b0  \emdash Authentication page\par
\b /admin/dashboard\b0  \emdash The main control centre\par
\b /admin/fleet-map\b0  \emdash Full-screen live map\par
\b /admin/emergencies\b0  \emdash Emergency alert management\par
\b /admin/fleet\b0  \emdash Bus fleet management\par
\b /admin/users\b0  \emdash User management (drivers, passengers, admins)\par
\b /admin/routes\b0  \emdash Route and bus stop management\par
\b /admin/audit-logs\b0  \emdash Admin action audit trail\par
\par}
I implemented \b authentication using React Context API\b0 . The AuthContext stores the admin session, handles login and logout, and persists the access token in localStorage. Every protected route checks the context before rendering \emdash unauthenticated access always redirects to login.\par
}
\par

{\f1\fs28\b\cf2 4.3 Dashboard Page\par}
\par
{\f1\fs22 The Dashboard is the first screen an admin sees after logging in. It is designed to give an immediate, at-a-glance overview of the entire bus network.\par
\par
\b Key features:\b0\par
{\pard\li720
\b Live statistics cards:\b0  Show active buses, passengers today, pending emergency alerts, and standby buses. These figures auto-refresh on a polling interval so the admin always sees current data without manually refreshing the page.\par
\b Mini live map:\b0  An embedded Leaflet map showing all buses currently on the road. Each bus is represented by a coloured circular marker. The colour is dynamic: \b green\b0  means the bus is running normally, \b amber\b0  means the bus is more than 50\% full, and \b red\b0  means the bus is over 80\% capacity or has broken down. The number displayed inside each marker is the current passenger count.\par
\b Notification panel:\b0  A bell icon in the header opens a sliding notification dropdown showing recent system alerts, driver sign-ups, and emergency events. Admins can mark individual notifications as read or clear all at once.\par
\b Active emergency strip:\b0  A list of the most recent unresolved emergency alerts is displayed directly on the dashboard, colour-coded by type \emdash red for Medical, orange for Accident, purple for Criminal, and orange-red for Breakdown.\par
\par}
The key technical decision on the Dashboard was using \b polling with setInterval\b0  rather than WebSockets for the statistics. This was a deliberate choice: the backend\rquote s data refresh rate is low enough that every-10-second polling is sufficient, and it avoids the complexity of maintaining a persistent WebSocket connection for non-critical UI elements.\par
}
\par

{\f1\fs28\b\cf2 4.4 Fleet Map Page\par}
\par
{\f1\fs22 The Fleet Map page is one of the most technically complex parts of the admin panel. It gives administrators a full-screen, interactive view of all buses, their routes, and their stops.\par
\par
\b Key features:\b0\par
{\pard\li720
\b Live bus markers:\b0  Every active bus appears as a clickable marker on the map. The size of the marker increases when selected so the admin can clearly see which bus they are inspecting.\par
\b Route polylines:\b0  When an admin selects a route from the sidebar, the system fetches road-accurate polylines from an OSRM (Open Source Routing Machine) API and draws them as coloured lines on the map. Each route has a unique colour assigned from a predefined palette.\par
\b Bus stop markers:\b0  Bus stops for each route are drawn as circular markers on the polyline.\par
\b Bus detail sidebar:\b0  Clicking any bus marker opens a side panel showing the bus number, registration plate, route, current passenger count and capacity, driver\rquote s name, phone number, email, and star rating.\par
\b Fly-to animation:\b0  When an admin selects a bus from the list, the map smoothly animates (using Leaflet\rquote s flyTo method) to centre on that bus\rquote s location.\par
\b Default coordinates:\b0  If a bus does not yet have a GPS fix, it falls back to Colombo Fort coordinates (6.9271, 79.8612) rather than crashing the map render.\par
\par}
The most interesting engineering challenge here was the \b route polyline system\b0 . Rather than drawing straight lines between stops, I integrated with an OSRM routing API to get road-following paths. I built a \b RouteLayer data structure\b0  that holds the route ID, colour, stop list, and polyline coordinates together, so the map can efficiently layer multiple routes with their stops and paths simultaneously.\par
}
\par

{\f1\fs28\b\cf2 4.5 Emergencies Page\par}
\par
{\f1\fs22 The Emergencies page allows administrators to view, filter, and respond to emergency alerts reported by drivers.\par
\par
\b Key features:\b0\par
{\pard\li720
\b Alert summary cards:\b0  Four stat cards at the top show total alerts, new alerts, responded alerts, and resolved alerts.\par
\b Filter panel:\b0  Admins can filter by status (New, Responded, Resolved) and by emergency type (Medical, Accident, Criminal, Breakdown) simultaneously.\par
\b Alert cards:\b0  Each alert shows a type icon, colour-coded by severity, the time it was reported, the location, and its current status.\par
\b Detail modal:\b0  Clicking an alert opens a full detail view with all the information about the incident.\par
\b Status workflow:\b0  Admins can transition an alert through the workflow: New \f2\fs20 \u8594?\f1\fs22  Responded \f2\fs20 \u8594?\f1\fs22  Resolved.\par
\b Deploy bus:\b0  Admins can deploy a standby bus to an emergency location directly from this screen.\par
\b View on map:\b0  Clicking \ldblquote View on Map\rdblquote  navigates to the Fleet Map page so the admin can see the emergency in geographic context.\par
\par}
The page polls the backend every 10 seconds, so new emergencies submitted by drivers appear without the admin needing to manually refresh.\par
}
\par

{\f1\fs28\b\cf2 4.6 Fleet Management Page\par}
\par
{\f1\fs22 This page allows administrators to manage the bus fleet inventory.\par
\par
\b Key features:\b0\par
{\pard\li720
\b Fleet stats bar:\b0  Shows total buses, active, standby, in-repair, and broken-down counts.\par
\b Bus table:\b0  A filterable table of all buses. Admins can filter by route and by status simultaneously.\par
\b Register new bus:\b0  A modal form allows registering a brand-new bus, assigning it a route and a driver.\par
\b Edit bus:\b0  Admins can reassign a bus to a different driver, update its registration, or change its route.\par
\b Status update:\b0  Admins can change a bus\rquote s operational status (Active, Standby, In Repair).\par
\par}
}
\par

{\f1\fs28\b\cf2 4.7 User Management Page\par}
\par
{\f1\fs22 This page manages the three types of users in the system: Drivers, Passengers, and Admins. I designed it as a \b tabbed interface\b0  so all three user types are accessible from one screen without navigation.\par
\par
\b Key features:\par\b0
{\pard\li720
\b Driver tab:\b0  Shows all drivers with their approval status. Admins can approve or reject new driver registrations, activate or suspend drivers, edit their details, or delete their accounts.\par
\b Passenger tab:\b0  Shows all registered passengers. Admins can suspend, activate, or delete passenger accounts.\par
\b Admin tab:\b0  Manages the admin accounts themselves. Super-admins can create, edit, or remove other administrators.\par
\b Search and filters:\b0  Each tab has a search bar plus status and route filters.\par
\b Inline forms:\b0  All add and edit operations are handled through modal dialogs, keeping the user on the same page rather than navigating away.\par
\par}
}
\par

{\f1\fs28\b\cf2 4.8 Routes Page\par}
\par
{\f1\fs22 The Routes page lets administrators manage bus routes and their stops.\par
\par
\b Key features:\b0\par
{\pard\li720\b Route cards:\b0  Each route is shown as a card with its route number, name, origin, destination, and a coloured accent.\par
\b CRUD operations:\b0  Admins can create new routes, edit existing ones, toggle a route\rquote s active status, or delete it.\par
\b Stops panel:\b0  Clicking a route opens a \b StopsPanel component\b0  that I built as a reusable sub-component. It lists all the bus stops on that route and allows adding, editing, or removing stops.\par
\par}
}
\par

{\f1\fs28\b\cf2 4.9 Audit Logs Page\par}
\par
{\f1\fs22 The Audit Logs page provides a complete, paginated record of every administrative action taken in the system.\par
\par
\b Key features:\b0\par
{\pard\li720\b Action badges:\b0  Each log entry has a colour-coded badge indicating the action type: green for CREATE and APPROVE, red for DELETE and REJECT, blue for UPDATE and LOGIN, amber for DEPLOY, and so on.\par
\b Date range filter:\b0  Admins can filter logs by date range.\par
\b Admin and action filters:\b0  Logs can also be filtered by which admin performed the action and what type of action it was.\par
\b Pagination:\b0  Logs are paginated at 50 records per page to keep the UI responsive.\par
\par}
This page was important from a governance and accountability perspective. Every significant action in the system \emdash creating a user, deploying a bus, resolving an emergency \emdash is recorded and traceable to a specific administrator.\par
}
