{\f1\fs28\b\cf2 5.1 Technology Stack \emdash Flutter Apps\par}
\par
{\f1\fs22 All three mobile apps are built with Flutter, using the following core packages:\par
\par
{\pard\li720
\b Flutter 3.8+ with Dart:\b0  Chosen for its single-codebase approach to Android and iOS development, excellent performance through native compilation, and a rich widget library.\par
\b Provider:\b0  For state management. I chose Provider because it is lightweight, officially recommended by the Flutter team, and keeps the separation between UI and business logic clean.\par
\b go_router:\b0  For declarative, URL-based navigation. This is important for handling deep links and the authenticated shell pattern.\par
\b flutter_map:\b0  For rendering maps, using OpenStreetMap tiles. This avoids Google Maps API billing and is fully open-source.\par
\b Supabase Flutter:\b0  For subscribing to Realtime bus location broadcasts.\par
\b Dio:\b0  For HTTP API communication with the backend, paired with a TokenService that automatically injects JWT tokens into every request header.\par
\b qr_flutter:\b0  For generating and rendering the passenger QR code.\par
\b flutter_secure_storage:\b0  For securely persisting authentication tokens on the device.\par
\b google_fonts:\b0  For clean, consistent typography across all apps.\par
\par}
All three apps share the same design language: a dark navy primary colour (\b #0A2342\b0 ), a medium blue secondary (\b #1565C0\b0 ), and a light grey surface (\b #F5F7FA\b0 ), creating a professional, transit-system aesthetic.\par
}
\par

{\f1\fs28\b\cf2 5.2 BusGo Client \emdash Passenger Mobile App\par}
\par
{\f1\fs22 The Passenger app is the primary public-facing product. It is used by bus commuters in Colombo to find buses, track them live, report emergencies, and manage their digital identity.\par
}
\par

{\f1\fs24\b\cf3 Authentication Flow\par}
\par
{\f1\fs22 The app opens on a \b Splash Screen\b0  that checks for a saved token and either navigates the user directly to the home screen or to the login screen. The \b Login Screen\b0  uses a staggered animation \emdash each form element fades and slides in with a slight delay, giving the screen a polished, app-like feel rather than a plain static form.\par
\par
I implemented \b Remember Me\b0  functionality using flutter_secure_storage, which persists the refresh token securely in the device\rquote s keychain so users stay logged in between app sessions. The Register screen handles new passenger sign-ups with field validation, and the Forgot Password screen sends a reset link via the backend.\par
}
\par

{\f1\fs24\b\cf3 Dashboard Screen\par}
\par
{\f1\fs22 The Dashboard is the main home screen of the passenger app. It shows:\par
{\pard\li720
\b Mini route map:\b0  A live-animated mini-map at the top showing the three main Colombo routes (138, 163, 171) with animated bus markers that actually move along the route polylines in real time, simulating live bus positions.\par
\b Nearby buses list:\b0  Below the map, a scrollable list of nearby buses shows each bus\rquote s route number, direction, distance from the user, and current passenger count with a crowd indicator.\par
\b BusCard widget:\b0  I built a reusable BusCard widget that is used both on the Dashboard and in the Search screen, ensuring visual consistency.\par
\b CrowdIndicator widget:\b0  A custom widget I designed that shows occupancy as a colour-coded bar \emdash green, amber, or red \emdash alongside a text label like \ldblquote Low\rdblquote , \ldblquote Moderate\rdblquote , or \ldblquote High\rdblquote .\par
\par}
The bus animation on the dashboard uses a \b Timer.periodic\b0  to advance each bus\rquote s position along its polyline every 3 seconds, creating a smooth real-time feel even in areas without a live GPS signal from the bus.\par
}
\par

{\f1\fs24\b\cf3 Live Map Screen\par}
\par
{\f1\fs22 The Live Map is the full-screen interactive map for passengers. It features:\par
{\pard\li720
\b Real route polylines:\b0  The app calls the OSRM routing API to fetch road-accurate polylines for all three bus routes simultaneously, so the lines follow actual roads rather than straight lines between stops.\par
\b Animated live buses:\b0  Three bus markers move along these polylines in real time. I used a custom interpolation algorithm to smoothly position each bus between waypoints based on elapsed time.\par
\b User location dot:\b0  A pulsing blue dot indicates the user\rquote s current position (set to Colombo Fort for demonstration). The pulse animation is implemented using a looping AnimationController.\par
\b Bus selection:\b0  Tapping a bus marker reveals a bottom card showing the route name, crowd level, and status.\par
\par}
}
\par

{\f1\fs24\b\cf3 Route Search Screen\par}
\par
{\f1\fs22 The Search screen allows passengers to find buses by destination:\par
{\pard\li720
A destination text field with a \b live autocomplete suggestion list\b0  that filters as the user types.\par
Results show all buses serving that destination with their route numbers, directions, and crowd levels.\par
\par}
