{\f1\fs32\b\cf2 SECTION 6 \emdash KEY TECHNICAL DECISIONS & JUSTIFICATIONS\par}
{\f1\fs20\cf6\i [Duration: ~3 minutes | Be ready to defend these choices]\par}
\par

{\f1\fs22 I want to highlight several technical decisions I made that the panel may ask about:\par
\par
\b 1. Why React for the Admin Panel and Flutter for mobile?\par\b0
{\pard\li720 React is the dominant library for building complex, data-driven web applications. Its component model and rich ecosystem made it ideal for a multi-page admin dashboard with many interactive tables, modals, and maps. Flutter was chosen for mobile because it compiles to native ARM code, giving smooth 60fps animations which are critical for a map-heavy application, and because a single codebase runs on both Android and iOS.\par}
\par
\b 2. Why Provider over other state management solutions in Flutter?\par\b0
{\pard\li720 Provider is lightweight, integrates naturally with Flutter\rquote s widget tree via InheritedWidget, and is officially recommended by the Flutter team. Given the complexity of our app \emdash which has Auth, Bus, Trip, User, and Emergency state domains \emdash Provider\rquote s multi-provider pattern kept each domain isolated and testable. More complex solutions like Bloc or Riverpod would have added boilerplate without significant benefit at our scale.\par}
\par
\b 3. Why React Context API for admin authentication rather than Redux or Zustand?\par\b0
{\pard\li720 Authentication state in the admin panel is relatively simple: it is either authenticated or not, and it rarely changes. Context API with a single AuthProvider was the right fit. Redux would have been over-engineering for this use case.\par}
\par
\b 4. Why OpenStreetMap / Leaflet / flutter_map instead of Google Maps?\par\b0
{\pard\li720 Google Maps requires a billing-enabled API key, which introduces cost uncertainty in a student project context. OpenStreetMap with Leaflet (web) and flutter_map (mobile) is fully open-source, freely available, and provides the same tile quality for our Colombo use case. The OSRM routing API provides road-accurate polylines without cost.\par}
\par
\b 5. Why Supabase Realtime for bus location instead of a custom WebSocket server?\par\b0
{\pard\li720 Supabase Realtime provides a managed, scalable pub/sub infrastructure that we can connect to directly from Flutter without building and maintaining a custom WebSocket server. For bus location broadcasting, where the backend pushes updates to all subscribed clients, this pattern is exactly what Realtime is designed for.\par}
\par
\b 6. Why TypeScript over plain JavaScript for the admin panel?\par\b0
{\pard\li720 The admin panel consumes multiple API endpoints with complex data shapes: buses, drivers, passengers, emergency alerts, routes, stops, audit logs. TypeScript\rquote s type system enforces that each API response is handled correctly, catching shape mismatches at compile time. Given the production-readiness goal of the project, TypeScript was a non-negotiable choice.\par}
}
\par\line\par

{\f1\fs32\b\cf2 SECTION 7 \emdash CHALLENGES & HOW I SOLVED THEM\par}
{\f1\fs20\cf6\i [Duration: ~2\endash 3 minutes | Show problem-solving ability]\par}
\par

{\f1\fs22 \b Challenge 1: Animating buses along road-accurate polylines in Flutter\par\b0
{\pard\li720 The live map in the passenger and driver apps needed to show buses moving smoothly along actual road paths, not in straight lines. The OSRM API returned polylines as lists of lat/lng coordinates, but animating a marker along hundreds of waypoints smoothly required a custom interpolation algorithm. I solved this by computing the cumulative distance of the polyline, then using a progress value (0.0 to 1.0) that advances each timer tick. The current position is calculated by finding which segment the progress falls into and linearly interpolating between those two coordinates. This gives smooth, continuous movement along the road shape.\par}
\par
\b Challenge 2: Displaying route polylines on the admin panel map\par\b0
{\pard\li720 The admin panel needed to show multiple route polylines simultaneously, each with a different colour, and each linked to its stops and buses. The challenge was that loading all routes, their stops, and their road polylines involves multiple async API calls. I designed a RouteLayer data structure that bundles the route ID, colour, stop list, and polyline together, and loaded all routes in parallel using Promise.all. Once all data was ready, the map rendered all layers atomically, preventing partial or flickering renders.\par}
\par
\b Challenge 3: Keeping the admin panel responsive across pages without a global state manager\par\b0
{\pard\li720 With eight separate pages each making their own API calls, I needed to ensure that data was fresh without over-fetching. I solved this through a consistent pattern: each page fetches its own data on mount using useEffect, uses polling (setInterval) only where live data is genuinely needed (Dashboard and Emergencies), and all service calls are centralised in a typed service layer so the same logic is never duplicated.\par}
\par
\b Challenge 4: Making the scanner viewfinder feel professional\par\b0
{\pard\li720 A scanner screen that feels like a real product needs precise visual feedback. I implemented two independent AnimationControllers in the scanner \emdash one for the scan line and one for the pulse glow \emdash with different durations and different easing curves (easeInOut for the scan line, linear for the pulse). Layering these with Stack and Positioned widgets produced the professional scanning UI without any third-party scanning animation library.\par}
}
