{\f1\fs32\b\cf2 SECTION 9 \emdash ANTICIPATED VIVA QUESTIONS & ANSWERS\par}
{\f1\fs20\cf6\i [Study these answers carefully]\par}
\par

{\f1\fs24\b\cf3 Q1: Why did you use React for the admin panel instead of a mobile app?\par}
{\f1\fs22 The admin panel is designed for desktop use by transport administrators who sit at workstations. A web application gives them a large screen with multiple data panels visible simultaneously \emdash something a mobile screen cannot offer. React\rquote s component-based architecture also made it straightforward to build complex multi-panel layouts like the split-view Fleet Map page.\par}
\par

{\f1\fs24\b\cf3 Q2: What is the difference between the three Flutter apps?\par}
{\f1\fs22 They serve three completely different actors. The Passenger app (BusGo Client) is for the general public \emdash finding buses, tracking them, holding a QR ticket. The Driver app (BusGo Drive) is for the person driving the bus \emdash it shows route information, passenger counts, and allows SOS reporting during a trip. The Scanner app (BusGo Scanner) is for the bus conductor \emdash its sole purpose is scanning passenger QR codes to validate tickets. Each app is scoped tightly to its user\rquote s role to keep the UI focused and easy to use in their specific context.\par}
\par

{\f1\fs24\b\cf3 Q3: How does the QR ticketing system work end to end?\par}
{\f1\fs22 When a passenger registers, the backend generates a unique QR code string for their account and stores it in their profile. The Passenger app\rquote s QR Card screen fetches this string from the backend via the UserProvider and renders it as a QR code image using the qr_flutter package. When the conductor opens the Scanner app and points it at the passenger\rquote s screen, the app reads the QR code value and verifies it against the backend. A valid code shows the Scan Success screen; an invalid or expired code shows the Scan Error screen.\par}
\par

{\f1\fs24\b\cf3 Q4: How does the live map work? Is it actually real-time?\par}
{\f1\fs22 The system has two layers of real-time data. In the mobile apps, Supabase Realtime is used to subscribe to bus location broadcasts pushed by the backend. Additionally, I implemented a client-side animation layer: even between Realtime updates, buses appear to move smoothly because the app animates markers along the known route polyline using timer-based interpolation. On the admin panel, bus positions are fetched through polling every few seconds via the REST API. For a production deployment with GPS hardware installed in buses, the Supabase Realtime channel would receive live GPS coordinates and broadcast them instantly.\par}
\par

{\f1\fs24\b\cf3 Q5: How did you handle authentication and security on the front end?\par}
{\f1\fs22 In the admin panel, authentication uses JWT tokens stored in localStorage. The AuthContext intercepts all API calls via an Axios instance and attaches the access token to every request header. If a call returns 401 (Unauthorised), the user is redirected to the login page. In the Flutter apps, tokens are stored using flutter_secure_storage, which uses the device\rquote s secure enclave (Android Keystore / iOS Keychain) so tokens cannot be read by other apps or through file system access. The TokenService wraps all token read/write operations, and the ApiClient automatically injects the token into every Dio request header.\par}
\par

{\f1\fs24\b\cf3 Q6: What would you improve if you had more time?\par}
{\f1\fs22 Several things. First, I would integrate actual GPS hardware tracking through the driver app so real bus positions replace the simulated movement. Second, I would add push notifications to the passenger app using Firebase Cloud Messaging so passengers receive alerts when their bus is approaching. Third, I would implement offline support in the Flutter apps using a local SQLite cache so the app is usable in low-connectivity areas, which is a real concern in suburban Sri Lanka. Fourth, I would add end-to-end tests for critical user flows like login, QR scanning, and emergency submission.\par}
\par

{\f1\fs24\b\cf3 Q7: How did you collaborate with your team as the front-end developer?\par}
{\f1\fs22 My work depended entirely on the REST API contracts provided by the backend team. We agreed on API request and response formats early in the project and I built a typed service layer in both React (TypeScript interfaces) and Flutter (Dart model classes) that formalized these contracts. This meant I could develop front-end features against consistent interfaces even before the backend endpoints were fully implemented, by using mock data services. Once the backend was ready, I swapped the mock services for real API calls with minimal changes to the UI layer.\par}
